      "writtenOn": "2026-05-12T14:35:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "`UnsupportedApplyTime` is more specific and can be further processed by applications like bmcweb. The specific meaning is that the update can be retried with a different `ApplyTime`.\n\n`InvalidArgument` could apply to any of the 3 existing error codes here as well so i am not sure why we have different error codes in the first place then?",
      "parentUuid": "d6e20ca8_a4d8e78c",
      "revId": "761946d22f42b06deeab58691f9375b14b1feb44",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6857fcce_e6352ade",
        "filename": "yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/Software/Update.interface.yaml",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 30,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000000
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-05-12T15:00:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e UnsupportedApplyTime is more specific and can be further processed by applications like bmcweb. The specific meaning is that the update can be retried with a different ApplyTime.\n\nIf we are expecting bmcweb to automatically deduce that it should try a different ApplyTime, why isn\u0027t the application doing that?  Is there something intrinsic to Redfish that says \"try this type and then promote it to this one\"?  That seems unusual.\n\n\u003e InvalidArgument could apply to any of the 3 existing error codes here as well so i am not sure why we have different error codes in the first place then?\n\nIf there is very specific value in this one, I\u0027m ok with it, but I don\u0027t want to get into the habit / convention of creating a new error type for every single method parameter.",
      "parentUuid": "dae94e2f_15a81b7f",
      "revId": "761946d22f42b06deeab58691f9375b14b1feb44",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "85ae5933_3fc90b3d",
